<section><title> Automonomous Equations </title>
	<introduction>

		<p>
			When the first-order differential equation <xref ref="yp-equals-fty"/> lacks <m>t</m> terms, then its form becomes:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dt}=f(y).
			</me>
			Such equations are called <em>autonomous differential equations</em>.
		</p>

		<p>
			The word "autonomous" means "self-governing." That fits, because the behavior of these equations is governed entirely by the current value of <m>y</m>, the current value of <m>t</m> doesn't matter. For example, a compressed spring gives the same force whether it's morning or afternoon.
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="def-autonomous-eqn"><title> Automonous Differential Equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					An <term>autonomous differential equation</term> is a differential equation of the form
					<men xml:id="autonomous-eqn">
						y' = f(y)
					</men>,
					where the change in <m>y</m> is only influenced by <m>y</m> itself.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs><title> Slope Fields of Automonomous Equations </title>
		<p>
			To visualize this, we can draw a slope field for an autonomous equation. For example, consider the equation:
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - \frac94.
		</me>

		<p>
			The slope at any point <m>(t, y)</m> depends only on <m>y</m>. So, the slope should change when <m>y</m> changes, but not when <m>t</m> changes. Since <m>y</m> changes in the vertical (up/down) direction, we should observe the slope change as we move up and down in the slope field. In constrast, we should not see the slope change in the horizontal where <m>t</m> changes.
		</p>

		<p>
			The slope field for this equation is given in <xref ref="ysqrd-4y-slope-field"/>. Starting at the bottom of the vertical rectangle and moving up, we see that the slope segment rotates counterclockwise, indicating an increasing slope. On the other hand, moving from left to right through the horizontal rectangle, we see that the slope segments remain parallel, indicating that the slope does not change as <m>t</m> changes.
		</p>

		<sidebyside widths="46%" margin="27%" valign="middle">
			<figure xml:id="ysqrd-4y-slope-field">
				<image>
					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}[declare function={f(\x,\y)=(\y)^2-2.25;}, scale=0.8]

							\pgfkeys{/pgf/number format/.cd,
								fixed,
								precision=1
							}
							\def\tmin{-0.5} \def\tmax{3}
							\def\ymin{-0.5} \def\ymax{3}
							\def\tstep{0.25}  \def\ystep{0.25}
							\def\arrowscale{0.2} % length of slope arrows
							\def\segmentwt{0.8pt} % thickness of slope segments

							% stepsize along t-axis and y-axis
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\tL}{\tmin + \tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\tR}{\tmax - \tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\yL}{\ymin + \ystep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\yR}{\ymax - \ystep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\nt}{(\tR-\tL)/\tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\ny}{(\yR-\yL)/\ystep}

							% Draw grid lines
							\foreach \i in {0,...,\nt} {
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\tk}{\tL + \i * \tstep}
								\draw[thin, gray!50] (\tk, \ymin) -- (\tk, \ymax);
							}
							\foreach \j in {0,...,\ny} {
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\yk}{\yL + \j * \ystep}
								\draw[thin, gray!50] (\tmin, \yk) -- (\tmax, \yk);
							}

							% Axes
							\draw[->] (\tmin, 0) -- (\tmax+0.3, 0) node[xshift=-0.1cm, font=\tiny, below] {$t$};
							\draw[->] (0, \ymin) -- (0, \ymax+0.3) node[yshift=-0.1cm, font=\tiny, left] {$y$};

							% Bounding box
							\draw[gray!50] (\tmin,\ymin) rectangle (\tmax,\ymax);

							% Tick marks and labels on t-axis
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\tLint}{\tL}
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\tRint}{\tR}
							\foreach \t in {\tLint,...,\tRint} {
								\pgfmathparse{\t &lt; 0}
								\ifnum\pgfmathresult=1	 % shift negative ticks
									\draw (\t,\ymin-0.06) -- (\t,\ymin+0.06)
									node[font=\tiny, below, xshift=-0.01cm] {\t};
								\else
									\draw (\t,\ymin-0.06) -- (\t,\ymin+0.06)
									node[font=\tiny, below] {\t};
								\fi
							}

							% Tick marks and labels on y-axis
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\yLint}{\yL}
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\yRint}{\yR}
							\foreach \y in {\yLint,...,\yRint}
								\draw (\tmin-0.06,\y) -- (\tmin+0.1,\y)
								node[font=\tiny, left] {\y};

							% Title
							%\node[above, font=\small\bfseries] at (current bounding box.north) 
							%	{Slope field for \quad $y' = x + y$};

							\draw[fill=blue!40!black] (\tmin,0.375) rectangle (\tmax,0.625);
							\draw (\tmax,0.8) node[font=\tiny, right, xshift=-0.1cm] {Constant};
							\draw[&lt;-] (\tmax,0.5) -- (\tmax+0.25,0.5) node[font=\tiny, right] {Slope};
							\draw[fill=green!40!black] (1.375,\ymin) rectangle (1.625,\ymax);
							\draw[&lt;-] (1.5, \ymax) -- (1.5, \ymax+0.25) node[font=\tiny, above, yshift=-0.1cm] {Changing Slope};

							% slope field: just draw a vector at each point
							\foreach \i in {0,...,\nt}
							\foreach \j in {0,...,\ny}{

								\pgfmathsetmacro{\tpt}{\tL + \i * \tstep}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\ypt}{\yL + \j * \ystep}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\slope}{f(\tpt,\ypt)}

								% Normalize direction vector (1, slope) to fixed length
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\len}{sqrt(1 + (\slope)^2)}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\dt}{\arrowscale / \len}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\dy}{\arrowscale * \slope / \len}

								\draw[teal!75, line width=\segmentwt, shift={(\tpt,\ypt)}] (-0.5*\dt, -0.5*\dy) -- (0.5*\dt, 0.5*\dy);
								%\draw[fill=white!50] (\tpt,\ypt) circle (1.5pt);
							}

						\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
				<caption>Slope field for <m>y' = y - t</m></caption>
			</figure>
		</sidebyside>

	</paragraphs>

	<conclusion><title> ðŸ“¤ Wrap-Up </title>	
		<paragraphs><title> Summary </title>
			<p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<p>
							First Order autonomous differential equations have the special form:
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y).
							</me>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							The slope field for these equations has a unique structure where the slope segments are parallel along horizontal lines, creating a "striped" pattern.
						</p>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</paragraphs>

		<paragraphs><title> Reading Questions </title>
			<exercise><title> Answer the Following </title>
				<task><title> Give the Slope </title>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Suppose you are looking at the slope field for the autonomous equation
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y),
							</me>
							and notice that the slope is <m>3</m> at the point <m>(2, 1)</m>, then what do you see when you look at the slope at the point <m>(-3, 1)</m>?
						</p>
					</statement>
					<choices>
						<choice correct="no">
							<statement>
								<p>
									<m>0</m>
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									This is incorrect. Carefully review the summary above.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="no">
							<statement>
								<p>
									<m>-3</m>
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									This is incorrect. Carefully review the summary above.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="no">
							<statement>
								<p>
									<m>1</m>
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									This is incorrect. Carefully review the summary above.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<p>
									<m>3</m>
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Yes, the slope at <m>(-3, 1)</m> is the same as at <m>(2, 1)</m> because the slope does not change when <m>t</m> changes.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="no">
							<statement>
								<p>
									Impossible to answer.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									This is incorrect. It is possible to answer this question based on the information given in the summary. Carefully review the summary above.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					
					</choices>
					
				</task>
				<task><title> Understanding Dependancy </title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							In the autonomous differential equation, 
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y),
							</me>
							the derivative, <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> does not depend on the independent variable, <m>t</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							This statement is false. This is a subtle but important detail. The slope that you get from <m>f(y)</m> at a point <m>(t,y)</m> does not change as <m>t</m> changes, but both <m>y</m> and its derivative, <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m>, are still functions of <m>t</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
			</exercise>
		</paragraphs>
	</conclusion>
</section>